Name: O-Desmethylangolensin
Description: Metabolite of daidzein.

Name: Equol
Description: Product of intestinal bacterial metabolism of dietary isoflavones (pmid:12468591).

Name: Enterolactone
Description: Mostly measured after enzymatic hydrolysis.

Name: Isorhamnetin
Description: Can coelute with tamarixetin.

Name: Tamarixetin
Description: Can coelute with isorhamnetin.

Name: Nitrogen
Description: Nitrogen can be measured in urine with the Kjeldahl method or by spectrophotometric methods (enzymic tests). Total urinary nitrogen is calculated based on urea urinary nitrogen quantified with these methods.

Name: Potassium
Description: Potassium is an alkali metal with valence 1. Potassium (K+) is the main cationic osmolyte within cells.

Name: Riboflavin
Description: Riboflavin, also known as vitamin B2, is a vitamin found in food and used as a dietary supplement.

Name: 4-Pyridoxic acid
Description: Metabolite of vitamin B6. Usually measured in urine.

Name: Vitamin B12
Description: Includes all vitamers with vitamin B12 activity. Complexe mixture of several compounds.

Name: Pantothenic acid
Description: Amide between pantoic acid and beta-alanine. An essential nutrient for many animals.

Name: Folates
Synonyms: Folic acid; Folate; Total folate; Folates, natural and synthetic; Folates, natural and added
Description: Includes natural folate (foods) and added folic acid (foods and/or supplements).

Name: Nicotinamide
Description: This item is used for "niacin" when niacin only includes "nicotinamide" and neither "nicotinic acid" nor "niacin equivalents".

Name: N-Methyl-2-pyridone-5-carboxamide
Description: Metabolite of nicotinamide.

Name: N-Methyl-4-pyridone-3-carboxamide
Description: Metabolite of nicotinamide.

Name: N-Methylnicotinamide
Description: Metabolite of nicotinamide.

Name: Ascorbic acid
Synonyms: Ascorbic acid, reduced; Vitamin C; L-Ascorbic acid; Ascorbate
Description: Reduced form of ascorbic acid.

Name: L-Dehydroascorbic acid
Synonyms: Ascorbic acid, oxidized; DHAA; Dehydroascorbic acid
Description: Oxidized form of ascorbic acid.

Name: 2,3-Diketogulonic acid
Description: Metabolite of ascorbic acid. Measured in urine.

Name: Sodium
Description: Sodium is an alkali metal with valence 1. Sodium (Na+) is the main cationic osmolyte in blood and extracellular fluid.

Name: Urea
Description: Biomarker of protein intake. Urea is the main nitrogen-containing substance in the urine of mammals.

Name: Tamarixetin/Isorhamnetin
Description: This item is used when tamarixetin and isorhamnetin coelute.

Name: 3,5-DHPPA
Description: Metabolite of alkylresorcinol.

Name: Dithiocarbamates
Description: Biomarker of cruciferous vegetable intake. Dithiocarbamate is obtained from conversion of isothiocyanates and measured after a cyclocondensation reaction.

Name: Iodine
Description: Iodine is a relatively volatile halogen with valences 1 through 7. Iodine typically is found and functions in its ionic form, iodide (I-).

Name: 5-Caffeoylquinic acid
Synonyms: Chlorogenic acid; 5-O-(3,4-Dihydroxycinnamoyl)-L-quinic acid; 3-Caffeoylquinic acid [Old IUPAC, before 1976]; CAS:202650-88-2; KEGG:C00852
Description: There is a confusion between two IUPAC nomenclatures. 5-CQA and 3-CQA should respectively correspond to chlorogenic acid and neochlorogenic acid. However many databases and publications still use the former nomenclature.

Name: N-Acetyl-S-(3-amino-2-hydroxy-3-oxopropyl)cysteine
Description: Metabolite of acrylamide.

Name: N-Acetyl-S-(3-amino-3-oxopropyl)cysteine
Description: Metabolite of acrylamide.

Name: 5-Hydroxytryptophol (5-HTOL) / 5-Hydroxyindole-3-acetic acid (5-HIAA)
Description: Metabolites of serotonin. Biomarker of recent ethanol intake.

Name: Phosphorus
Description: Phosphorus has 3 or 5 valences with oxidation states between -3 and +5. Phosphate (PO4 3-) - also called inorganic phosphate (Pi) - is the form utilized by humans.

Name: Taurine
Description: Derivative of cysteine. Widely distributed in animal tissues and major bile constituent. Often called an amino acid, it is not an amino acid.

Name: 2-Hydroxynaphthalene
Description: Biomarker of PAH exposure.

Name: Bisphenol A (BPA)
Description: Diet is considered to be the primary source of exposure to BPA through leaching from food packaging, but non-food sources may also contribute through dermal exposure or through inhalation (Geens et al., 2012).

Name: 2,4-Dichlorophenol (2,4-DCP)
Description: Metabolite of 2,4-D. Used in the synthesis of phenoxy herbicides including 2,4-D.

Name: 2,5-Dichlorophenol (2,5-DCP)
Description: Metabolite of 1,4-dichlorobenzene (1,4-DCB). 1,4-DCB is used in the production of insecticides and in products such as mothballs and toilet deodorant blocks.

Name: Monoethyl phthalate (MEP)
Description: Metabolite of diethyl phthalate (DEP).

Name: DBP metabolites
Synonyms: Di-butyl-phthalates metabolites; DnBP and DiBP metabolites; Mono-butyl-phthalates (MBP)
Description: Mono-n-butyl (DnBP metabolite) and mono-iso-butyl-phthalate (DiBP metabolite).

Name: Monobenzyl phthalate (MBzP)
Description: Metabolite of butyl benzyl phthalate (BBzP).

Name: Mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP)
Description: Metabolite of di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP).

Name: Mono(2-ethyl-5-hydroxyhexyl) phthalate (MEHHP)
Description: Metabolite of mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP); secondary metabolite of di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP).

Name: Mono(2-ethyl-5-oxohexyl) phthalate (MEOHP)
Description: Metabolite of mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP); secondary metabolite of di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP).

Name: Mono(2-ethyl-5-carboxypentyl) phthalate (MECPP)
Description: Metabolite of mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP); secondary metabolite of di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP).

Name: Mono-n-octyl phthalate (MnOP)
Description: Metabolite of di-n-octyl phthalate (DnOP).

Name: Mono-isononyl phthalate (MiNP)
Description: Metabolite of di-isononyl phthalate (DiNP). One of the various possible esters is represented.

Name: Mono-hydroxy-isononyl phthalate (OH-MiNP)
Synonyms: Mono(hydroxy-isononyl) phthalate; Mono(hydroxy-isononyl) phthalates; MHINP; MHNP; 7-OH-MiNP; 7-Hydroxy-(mono-methyl-octyl) phthalate; Mono(4-methyl-7-hydroxyoctyl) phthalate; Mono(4-methyl-7-hydroxy-octyl) phthalate; 7-OH-MMeOP; 7OH-MMeOP
Description: Metabolite of mono-isononyl phthalate (MiNP); secondary metabolite of di-isononyl phthalate (DiNP). Structure for 4-methyl-7-OH- is represented.

Name: Mono-oxo-isononyl phthalate (oxo-MiNP)
Synonyms: Mono(oxo-isononyl) phthalate; Mono(oxo-isononyl) phthalates; MOiNP; MONP; 7-Oxo-MiNP; 7-Oxo-(mono-methyl-octyl) phthalate; Mono(4-methyl-7-oxo-octyl) phthalate; 7oxo-MMeOP
Description: Metabolite of mono-isononyl phthalate (MiNP); secondary metabolite of di-isononyl phthalate (DiNP). Structure for 4-methyl-7-oxo- is represented.

Name: Mono-n-butyl phthalate (MnBP)
Description: Metabolite of di-n-butyl phthalate (DnBP).

Name: Mono-isobutyl phthalate (MiBP)
Description: Metabolite of di-isobutyl phthalate (DiBP).

Name: 3-Phenoxybenzoic acid (PBA)
Description: Metabolite of several pyrethroid insecticides.

Name: Mono(2-carboxymethylhexyl) phthalate (MCMHP)
Description: Metabolite of mono(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (MEHP); secondary metabolite of di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate (DEHP).

Name: Proline betaine
Description: An abundant component of citrus fruits.

Name: Hesperetin glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Hesperetin substitued with glucuronide at unknown position (3 possibilities).

Name: N-Acetyl-S-(N-allylthiocarbamoyl)cysteine
Description: N-Acetylcysteine conjugate of AITC (allyl isothiocyanate); a major urinary metabolite after ingestion of mustard.

Name: Sulforaphane N-acetyl-cysteine
Description: Metabolite of sulforaphane. Sulforaphane is obtained from glucoraphanin in cruciferous vegetables (e.g. broccoli).

Name: 5-Hydroxyindole-3-acetic acid
Description: Metabolite of serotonin, produced by host (Fig 2, pmid:29902437). Main metabolite of serotonin.

Name: 6-AMMU
Description: Metabolite of theobromine. Structure given by HMDB (and CHEBI) is wrong; correct one found in this document: https://monographs.iarc.fr/ENG/Monographs/vol51/mono51-12.pdf.

Name: Theobromine
Description: Found in cacao plant, chocolate and a number of other foods.

Name: 7-Methyluric acid
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: HHPAA sulfate
Description: HHPAA substituted with sulfate. HHPAA is a transformation product of the benzoxazinoid HBOA, found in cereal grains and bakery products.

Name: 3,5-DHPPA sulfate
Synonyms: DHPPA sulfate; 3-(3,5-Dihydroxyphenyl) propanoic acid sulfate; Dihydroxyphenylpropionic acid 3-sulfate; Dihydroxyphenylpropionic acid sulfate
Description: Sulfate of DHPPA, an alkylresorcinol metabolite.

Name: Caffeic acid sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Caffeic acid substituted with sulfate at unknown position (2 possibilities).

Name: HPAA sulfate
Synonyms: N-(2-Hydroxyphenyl) acetamide sulfate; Hydroxyphenyl acetamide sulfate
Description: HPAA substituted with sulfate. HPAA is a transformation product of the benzoxazinoids, found in cereal grains and bakery products.

Name: HHPAA
Description: HHPAA is a transformation product of the benzoxazinoid HBOA, found in cereal grains and bakery products (Adhikari 2015, pmid:25600612).

Name: Feruloylquinic acid
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Quinic acid substituted with ferulic acid at unknown position (3 possibilities).

Name: Feruloylquinic acid glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Quinic acid substituted with ferulic acid (3 possibilities) and glucuronide (2 possibilities) at unknown positions.

Name: Hydroxyhippuric acid
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Hippuric acid hydroxylated at unknown position.

Name: Dihydrocaffeic acid sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Dihydrocaffeic acid substituted with sulfate at unknown position (2 possibilities).

Name: Ethylcatechol glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Catechol substituted with ethyl (2 possibilities) and glucuronide (2 possibilities) at unknown positions.

Name: Gallic acid ethyl ester sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Gallic acid ethyl ester substituted with sulfate at unkown position (2 possibilities).

Name: Hydroxytyrosol sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Hydroxytyrosol substituted with sulfate at unkown position (2 possibilities).

Name: Dihydroresveratrol glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Dihydroresveratrol substituted with glucuronide at unknown position (3 possibilities).

Name: Naringenin glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Naringenin substituted with glucuronide at unkown position (3 possibilities).

Name: Hesperetin glucuronide sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Hesperetin substituted with glucuronide and sulfate at unkown positions (several possibilities).

Name: Methylgallic acid sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Gallic acid methylated (2 possibilities) and substituted with sulfate (3 possibilities) at unknown positions.

Name: Dihydroxyphenyl-gamma-valerolactone sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Dihydroxyphenyl-gamma-valerolactone substituted with sulfate at unknown position (2 possibilities). 5-(3',4'-Dihydroxyphenyl)-gamma-valerolactone (DHPV) reported to be the major microbial metabolite of proanthocyanidins.

Name: Pyrogallol sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Pyrogallol (1,2,3-Trihydroxybenzene) substituted with sulfate at unknown position (2 possibilities).

Name: Hydroxyphenylvaleric acid glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure.

Name: Methyl(epi)catechin sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure.

Name: Phloretin glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Phloretin substituted with glucuronide at unknown position. Phloretin 2-glucuronide is well known, but others are possible too.

Name: 4-Hydroxy-(3',4'-dihydroxyphenyl)valeric acid sulfate
Description: Undefined chemical structure. 4-Hydroxy-(3',4'-dihydroxyphenyl)valeric acid substituted with sulfate at unknown position (several possibilities).

Name: Dihydroxyphenyl-gamma-valerolactone glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Dihydroxyphenyl-gamma-valerolactone substituted with glucuronide at unknown position (2 possibilities). 5-(3',4'-Dihydroxyphenyl)-gamma-valerolactone (DHPV) reported to be the major microbial metabolite of proanthocyanidins.

Name: Tartaric acid
Synonyms: L-Tartaric acid; L-(+)-Tartaric acid; L-(R,R)-(+)-Tartaric acid; Threaric acid
Description: Tartaric acid is chiral. The naturally occurring form of the acid is dextrotartaric acid or L-(+)-tartaric acid.

Name: Erucin N-acetyl-cysteine
Description: Metabolite of erucin. Erucin is obtained from glucoerucin in cruciferous vegetables (e.g. arugula, kohlrabi and Chinese cabbage).

Name: N-Acetyl-(N'-benzylthiocarbamoyl)-cysteine
Description: Cysteine conjugate of acetyl benzyl isothiocyanate.

Name: Sulforaphane N-cysteine
Description: Metabolite of sulforaphane. Sulforaphane is obtained from glucoraphanin in cruciferous vegetables (e.g. broccoli).

Name: Trimethylamine N-oxide
Description: Generated from choline, betaine, and carnitine via gut microbial metabolism. Formed from trimethylamine (TMA) in the liver.

Name: Carnosine
Description: A naturally occurring dipeptide neuropeptide found in muscles.

Name: Diaminopimelic acid
Description: The meso-isomer of 2,6-diaminopimelic acid is a key constituent of bacterial peptidoglycan; it is often found in human urine due to the breakdown of the gut microbes (chebi). It is a lysine derivative.

Name: Trimethylamines
Description: Sum of trimethylamine and trimethylamine oxide (TMA + TMAO)

Name: Phenol
Description: Biomarker of benzene exposure.

Name: p-Cresol
Description: Microbial metabolite identified in gut (table 1 from Donia 2015).

Name: Creatinine
Description: This item is used in the database to indicate measurement or correlation adjustment; in these cases creatinine excretions are indicated. Can be quantified with the Jaffe Kinetic method.

Name: N-Propan-1-ol
Synonyms: 1-Propanol; n-Propanol; n-Propyl alcohol; Ethyl carbinol; Propanol

Name: MeIQx metabolites
Description: MeIQx (2-Amino-3,8-dimethyl-imidazo[4,5-f]quinoxaline) and its metabolites.

Name: 3-Hydroxyproline betaine
Description: A probable biostransformation product of proline betaine at C3.

Name: 4-Hydroxyproline betaine
Description: A component of citrus fruits, present at lower concentrations than proline betaine.

Name: 1,3,7-Trimethyluric acid
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: 1,3-Dimethyluric acid
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: 1,7-Dimethyluric acid
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: 1-Methyluric acid
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: 1-Methylxanthine
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: CMPF
Description: A furan fatty acid metabolite. A potent uremic toxin that has been found to accumulate in human serum of patients with chronic kidney diseases.

Name: AAMU
Description: Metabolite of caffeine. Derivative of the pyrimidine uracil.

Name: AFMU
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: alpha-CEHC glucuronide
Description: Glucuronide of alpha-CEHC, the major urinary metabolite of alpha-tocopherol that appears in human urine after vitamin E supplementation.

Name: alpha-CEHC sulfate
Description: Sulfate of alpha-CEHC, the major urinary metabolite of alpha-tocopherol that appears in human urine after vitamin E supplementation.

Name: Ethyl glucuronide
Description: Metabolite of ethanol. Biomarker of ethanol intake.

Name: Nicotinic acid
Synonyms: Niacin; Nicotinic acid; Nicotinate; Vitamin B3
Description: This item is used for "niacin" when niacin only includes "nicotinic acid" and neither "nicotinamide" nor "niacin equivalents".

Name: Nicotine
Description: Natural product of tobacco. Aso naturally occurs in smaller amounts in plants from the family Solanaceae (such as potatoes, tomatoes, and eggplant).

Name: Paraxanthine
Description: Metabolite of caffeine.

Name: Quinic acid
Description: Quinic acid possesses 8 possible stereosisomers (four meso forms and two pairs of enantiomers) [pmid: 27513177].

Name: Theophylline
Description: Structurally similar to caffeine and found in tea and cocoa.

Name: Trigonelline
Description: Metabolite of niacin with no vitamin activity. Occurs in many plants; abundant in coffee.

Name: Xylitol
Description: Xylitol is naturally found in many fruits and vegetables. It is used as a diabetic sweetener.

Name: beta-Carotene
Description: beta-Carotene is the most well-known provitamin A carotenoid.

Name: Lutein/Zeaxanthin
Synonyms: Lutein and Zeaxanthin; Lutein + Zeaxanthin; Lutein plus Zeaxanthin; Lutein; trans-Lutein/Zeaxanthin
Description: Can abusively be called "lutein". This item is used when lutein and zeaxanthin coelute. It is used by default for the intakes unless "lutein only" is clearly stated.

Name: alpha-Tocopherol
Description: The most important compound with vitamin E activity.

Name: Lutein
Description: Can coelute with zeaxanthin. This item is only used when "lutein only" is clearly stated, otherwise "Lutein/Zeaxanthin" should be used.

Name: Zeaxanthin
Description: Can coelute with lutein.

Name: Eicosadienoic acid (cis-20:2n-6)
Synonyms: Dihomolinoleic acid; Dihomolinoleate; all-cis-11,14-Eicosadienoic acid; (11Z,14Z)-Eicosadienoic acid; 20:2n6; 20:2n6,9

Name: Vitamin C
Description: Includes all vitamers with vitamin C activity: they are principally ascorbic acid and dehydroascorbic acid.

Name: Retinol
Synonyms: Vitamin A; Retinol; Preformed vitamin A

Name: Triglycerides
Description: This item is only used to indicate measurement or correlation adjustment; in these cases triglyceride excretions are indicated. Triglyceride intakes and triglyceride correlations are not included.

Name: Cholesterol
Description: This item is only used to indicate measurement or correlation adjustment; in these cases cholesterol excretions are indicated. Cholesterol intakes and cholesterol correlations are not included.

Name: Vitamin A (Carotenoids)
Synonyms: Carotene; Carotenes; Provitamin A; Provitamin A carotenoids
Description: Includes provitamin A carotenoids such as beta-carotene, alpha-carotene, and beta-cryptoxanthin.

Name: Vitamin A (Retinol Equivalents)
Description: Was traditionally used to describe total vitamin A activity. RE Vitamin A = mcg retinol + (mcg beta-carotene equivalents/6). See: http://www.ncc.umn.edu/products/databaseNUTvitamins.html.

Name: p,p'-DDE
Description: Metabolite of DDT, an organochlorine pesticide.

Name: 25-Hydroxycholecalciferol
Synonyms: Calcidiol; Calcifediol; 25-OH-Vitamin D; Vitamin D (in blood)
Description: Metabolite of vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol). Major circulating form of vitamin D, prehormone. Laboratory test for vitamin D status.

Name: Homocysteine
Description: Marker of folate deficiency.

Name: Pyridoxal 5'-phosphate
Description: Active form of vitamin B6.

Name: 3-Hydroxyphenylpropionic acid
Synonyms: 3-Hydroxyphenylpropionate; 3-(3'-Hydroxyphenyl)propionic acid; 3-(3-Hydroxyphenyl)propionic acid; 3-(3-Hydroxyphenyl)propanoic acid; Dihydro-3-coumaric acid; m-Hydroxyphenylpropionate

Name: 1-Docosahexaenoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine (PC(22:6/0:0))
Description: Isomer of lysoPhosphatidylcholine acyl C22:6.

Name: 4-Androsten-3beta,17beta-diol disulfate 1
Description: In litterature, there is a 4-Androsten-3beta,17beta-diol disulfate 1 and a 2. But the structures were not shown.

Name: Bilirubin isomer
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Bilirubin is a heme degradation product excreted in bile and urine. Its naturally occurring isomer is the Z,Z-isomer. Some of the double-bonds in bilirubin isomerize when exposed to light.

Name: Methyl palmitic acid isomer
Synonyms: Methyl hexadecanoic acid; Methyl palmitic acid; 2/15-Methyl palmitic acid
Description: Undefined chemical structure. Palmitic acid methylated at unknown position.

Name: Threonic acid
Description: L-Threonic acid is a metabolite of ascorbic acid (vitamin C).

Name: Indolepropionic acid
Synonyms: 3-Indolepropionic acid; Indolepropionate; 1H-Indole-3-propionic acid; IPA; Indole-3-propionate; Indole-3-propionic acid
Description: Microbial metabolite identified in gut (table 1 from Donia 2015). Metabolite of tryptophan, produced by bacteria (Fig 2, pmid:29902437). Gut microbiota metabolite of tryptophan (Fig 1, pmid:30120222).

Name: Selenium
Description: Selenium is a nonmetallic element with potential oxidation states +6, +4, and -2. Inorganic forms of selenium include selenide (H2Se), selenite (H2SeO3), and selenate (H2SeO4).

Name: 1,25-Dihydroxycholecalciferol
Description: Metabolite of vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol). Biologically active form of vitamin D (hormone).

Name: Pyridoxal
Description: Pyridoxal is a form of vitamin B6.

Name: 11-Eicosenoic acid (cis-20:1n-9)
Synonyms: cis-11-Eicosenoic acid; Eicosenoic acid; Gondoic acid; 20:1n-9

Name: D-Lactic acid
Description: Major end-product of bacterial metabolism in the large bowel (Cummings 1997). D-Lactic acid is the D-isomer of lactic acid. L-Lactic acid is the most common of the two isomers in living organisms.

Name: Tryptophan
Description: Essential amino acid. Precursor to the neurotransmitter serotonin, the hormone melatonin and vitamin B3.

Name: Kynurenine
Description: Metabolite of tryptophan, mostly produced by host, can be regulated by bacteria (Fig 2, pmid:29902437).

Name: Glutamic acid
Synonyms: L-Glutamic acid; (S)-Glutamic acid; (S)-2-Aminopentanedioic acid; alpha-Aminoglutaric acid

Name: L-Lactic acid
Description: Major end-product of bacterial metabolism in the large bowel (Cummings 1997). L-Lactic acid is the most common of the two lactic acid isomers in living organisms.

Name: Nt-Methylimidazoleacetic acid
Synonyms: N-Methylimidazoleacetic acid; 1-Methyl-4-imidazoleacetic acid; Methylimidazoleacetic acid; Tele-Methylimidazoleacetic acid; Ntau-Methylimidazoleacetic acid
Description: Metabolite of histamine (pmid:6524522).

Name: Orotic acid
Description: An intermediate product in pyrimidine synthesis which plays a role in chemical conversions between dihydrofolate and tetrahydrofolate.

Name: Methylsuccinic acid
Synonyms: 2-Methylsuccinic acid; 1,2-Propanedicarboxylic acid; Pyrotartaric acid; 2-Methylbutanedioic acid; DL-Methylsuccinic acid

Name: Phytofluene
Description: Isomery unknown. However most present in nature as all-trans-phytofluene and 15-cis-phytofluene (cis-phytofluene); 15-cis predominant in plants (Gupta2015) and all-trans predominant in serum (Hsu2012).

Name: Phytoene
Description: Isomery unknown. However most present in nature as all-trans-phytoene and 15-cis-phytoene (cis-phytofluene); 15-cis predominant in plants (Gupta2015) and all-trans predominant in serum (Hsu2012).

Name: Palmitelaidic acid (trans-16:1n-7)
Description: The trans-isomer of palmitoleic acid and predominant trans-16:1 isomer in cheeses from goat and ewe milk. Major dietary sources are partly hydrogenated vegetable oils.

Name: Fatty acids, trans
Description: Not necessarily all-trans fatty acids, can include fatty acids with a cis/trans conformation, but can't include all-cis fatty acids.

Name: 6-9E-Octadecenoic acids (trans-18:1n-9-12)
Description: Co-elution of the n-12 to n-9 trans isomers of C18:1.

Name: Retinyl palmitate
Description: Common vitamin A supplement.

Name: Cotinine
Description: Biomarker of tobacco smoke exposure. Metabolite of nicotine.

Name: Ellagic acid
Description: Ellagic acid is a dimeric derivative of gallic acid found as part of polymeric molecules called ellagitannins.

Name: 5-n-(16-Heneicosenyl)-resorcinol (C21:1) glucuronide
Description: Undefined chemical structure. The position of the double bond is unknown.

Name: Methylmalonic acid (MMA)
Description: Inverse biomarker of vitamin B12.

Name: Cholic acid
Classification: Trihydroxy bile acids, alcohols and derivatives
Description: Together with chenodeoxycholic acid, one of the two primary bile acid synthesized in the human liver (pmid:16299351).

Name: Glycocholic acid
Description: Glycine conjugate of cholic acid.

Name: Taurocholic acid
Classification: Trihydroxy bile acids, alcohols and derivatives
Description: Taurine conjugate of cholic acid.

Name: Glycodeoxycholic acid
Description: Glycine conjugate of deoxycholic acid.

Name: Chenodeoxycholic acid
Classification: Dihydroxy bile acids, alcohols and derivatives
Description: Together with cholic acid, one of the two primary bile acid synthesized in the human liver (pmid:16299351).

Name: Glycochenodeoxycholic acid
Description: Glycine conjugate of chenodeoxycholic acid.

Name: Taurochenodeoxycholic acid
Synonyms: TCDCA; Taurochenodeoxycholate; Chenyltaurine; Chenodeoxycholyltaurine; Desoxycholyltaurine; Taurochenoxycholate?; Taurochenoxycholic acid?
Description: Taurine conjugate of chenodeoxycholic acid.

Name: Glycoursodeoxycholic acid
Synonyms: N-(3alpha,7beta-Dihydroxy-5beta-cholanoyl)-glycine; Glycoursodeoxycholate; Glycine ursodeoxycholic acid; Ursodeoxycholylglycine; GUDCA
Description: Glycine conjugate of ursodeoxycholic acid.

Name: Glycolithocholic acid
Description: Glycine conjugate of lithocholic acid.

Name: Norepinephrine
Description: Neurotransmitter. Produced by gut bacteria (pmid:29903615).

Name: Pyridoxine
Description: Pyridoxine, also known as vitamin B6, is a form of vitamin B6 found commonly in food and used as dietary supplement.

Name: Pyridoxamine
Description: Pyridoxamine is a form of vitamin B6.

Name: Dimethylglycine
Description: A byproduct of the metabolism of choline.

Name: Phytanic acid
Description: Phytanic acid is found in the diet in dairy products, ruminant animal fats, and certain fish. It is metabolised into pristanic acid.

Name: Thymine
Description: One of the four main bases found in DNA and RNA, which are adenine, cytosine, guanine, and thymine (uracil in RNA).

Name: Hydroxytyrosol
Description: Commonly found in olive oil. Minor metabolite of dopamin. Putative biomarker of ethanol intake.

Name: 2,9-Hydroxyphenanthrene
Description: Biomarker of PAH exposure.

Name: 4-Monochlorophenol (4-MCP)
Description: Metabolite of chlorobenzene. Chlorobenzene is used in stain removers, solvents, herbicides, for the production of pharmaceutics and cosmetics, in paints, fungicides and drugs.

Name: Pentachlorophenol (PCP)
Description: Former herbicide, insecticide, fungicide, algaecide, disinfectant, and ingredient in antifouling paint.

Name: Mono(3-carboxypropyl) phthalate (MCPP)
Description: Non-specific metabolite of several phthalates. Metabolite of mono-n-butyl phthalate (MnBP); secondary metabolite of di-n-butyl phthalate (DnBP). Metabolite of mono-n-octyl phthalate (MnOP); secondary metabolite of di-n-octyl phthalate (DnOP).

Name: Isothiocyanates
Description: Biomarker of cruciferous vegetable intake. Isothiocyanates are derived from the hydrolysis of glucosinolates.
